-- Enrichment marathon batch: GitGuardian, Gitleaks, Gladly, Gladys, Glassbox, Glean, Glide, GlitchTip

-- в”Ђв”Ђ GitGuardian в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GitGuardian is a code security platform that detects hardcoded secrets, manages non-human identities, and monitors public and private repositories, CI/CD pipelines, and developer endpoints for exposed credentials.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (paid plans are quote-based)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$150-200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GitGuardian Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GitGuardian review 2026: secrets detection, non-human identity governance, pricing tiers, features, pros and cons, and top alternatives compared.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GitGuardian is a code and application security company built around a single, urgent problem: developers accidentally commit passwords, API keys, database credentials, and other secrets into source code, and those leaks are routinely exploited by attackers within minutes of exposure. The company was founded in Paris in 2017 by Eric Fourrier and Jeremy Thomas, who were working as a data scientist and software engineer and began by building a system that scanned GitHub's public commit stream in real time, flagging exposed credentials before they could be abused. That original public-monitoring engine became the technical core of the company and remains one of its most distinctive capabilities: GitGuardian continuously watches public GitHub activity for leaked secrets belonging to its customers, a feature few competitors replicate at the same scale. From that starting point, GitGuardian expanded into a broader internal-facing platform for organizations, covering private repositories, continuous integration and deployment pipelines, container images, messaging apps like Slack and Teams, and, more recently, developer laptops themselves through its Developer Endpoint Protection capability built into the ggshield command-line tool. The company has raised roughly 118 million dollars across five funding rounds, most recently a 50 million dollar Series C in February 2026, with investors including Insight Partners, Quadrille Capital, Eurazeo, Sapphire Ventures, and La French Tech among others. Earlier backers include Balderton Capital and Bpifrance. This funding trajectory places GitGuardian among the more established players in the DevSecOps and application security space, alongside its transition from a narrowly focused secrets-detection tool into a wider non-human identity, or NHI, security platform. Technically, GitGuardian's detection engine combines regular-expression pattern matching, entropy analysis, and specific and generic detectors for more than 450 (and by some counts over 550) distinct types of secrets, spanning cloud provider keys (AWS, Azure, GCP), database connection strings, private SSH and TLS keys, and vendor-specific tokens for services such as Stripe, Slack, and Twilio. Findings can be exported in SARIF format for direct integration with GitHub Advanced Security's code-scanning alerts, and the platform ships native integrations for GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, and Azure DevOps, plus pre-commit and pre-push git hooks so secrets can be blocked before they ever leave a developer's machine. Beyond detection, GitGuardian's NHI Governance module inventories non-human identities such as service accounts, API keys, and machine credentials, tracks their permissions and usage patterns, and recommends remediation and rotation workflows to centralize their lifecycle management, an increasingly important concern as organizations run more automated pipelines and AI agents that hold their own credentials. Honeytokens are another differentiated feature: GitGuardian generates decoy credentials that customers plant across their codebase, cloud storage, or developer endpoints, and if an attacker or infostealer malware ever attempts to use one, GitGuardian fires an instant, attributed alert well before real damage occurs. GitGuardian's pricing follows a per-developer-seat freemium model. The free Starter tier covers up to 25 developers with unlimited real-time scanning, up to 500 historical secret detections, git hooks, basic specific and generic detectors, and 10,000 API calls per month, with no credit card required. The Business (formerly Teams) tier, aimed at organizations of 26 to 200 developers, adds remediation playbooks, support for up to 20 teams, roughly 12 GB of repository scanning, custom regex detectors, SAML single sign-on, 100,000 API calls per month, and ticket-based support; pricing is quote-based rather than published. The Enterprise tier, for 200 or more developers, layers on Public Secrets Monitoring (the original public-GitHub watch capability extended to enterprise scale), NHI Governance with honeytokens, self-hosted deployment options, unlimited teams and API calls, unlimited custom detectors, push-to-vault workflows, and a dedicated support channel; this tier is also fully custom-quoted. GitGuardian's target audience skews toward security and platform engineering teams inside mid-size to large software organizations, particularly in regulated or security-conscious industries such as financial services, cloud infrastructure, and enterprise software, where a single leaked credential can trigger a costly breach. Publicly referenced customers include Snowflake, ING, BASF, and DigitalOcean, and the company states its tools are used by more than 600,000 developers worldwide. In the competitive landscape, GitGuardian sits alongside the open-source secret scanner Gitleaks and TruffleHog, GitHub's own built-in secret scanning and push protection (part of GitHub Advanced Security), and newer entrants such as Aikido Security, Spectral, and Legit Security. GitGuardian differentiates itself from the open-source tools primarily through its hosted dashboard, public-monitoring network effect, incident workflow and remediation tooling, honeytoken deception technology, and the newer NHI governance and endpoint protection layers, which position it less as a point scanner and more as a full non-human identity security platform. As AI-assisted coding tools proliferate and generate more code (and more accidental secrets) at higher velocity, GitGuardian has also begun shipping agent skills aimed at detecting and remediating secrets introduced by AI coding assistants, signaling where the company sees its next growth vector. Overall, GitGuardian's combination of real-time public monitoring, deep enterprise integrations, and an expanding non-human identity governance suite has made it one of the more recognized and well-funded vendors in the secrets management and code security category as of 2026.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f79bb617-e492-4f3f-b2e0-6a6ffd43dc71';

