-- в”Ђв”Ђ Gladly в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gladly is a customer service platform built around a single, lifelong customer timeline instead of ticket queues, combining voice, chat, email, and SMS with an AI automation layer called Sidekick.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$180 per agent per month (billed annually, 10-agent minimum)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$220-240 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gladly Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gladly review 2026: the people-centered customer service platform's features, Sidekick AI, Hero and Superhero pricing, pros, cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gladly is a customer service software platform founded in 2014 in San Francisco by Michael Wolfe, Joseph Ansanelli, and Dirk Kessler, a founding team with prior experience building and selling enterprise software companies. The company's core premise is a deliberate departure from the ticket-based model that dominates the customer support category. Where tools like Zendesk or Freshdesk organize work around discrete tickets or cases, Gladly organizes work around a single, continuous timeline for each customer, one that persists across every channel, voice, email, chat, SMS, and social messaging, and across every interaction that customer has ever had with a brand. The pitch to customer service leaders is that this 'people, not tickets' architecture lets agents see full context instantly, avoid asking customers to repeat themselves, and treat support as a relationship-building opportunity rather than a queue to clear. Gladly has raised a total of roughly 208 million dollars in venture funding from investors including Greylock Partners, New Enterprise Associates, GGV Capital, and AXA Venture Partners (AVP), which led a 40 million dollar round intended to fund the buildout of the company's AI-powered unified customer service platform. A separate, earlier round brought in 55 million dollars specifically earmarked for platform innovation. The company has grown to roughly 220 to 240 employees as of 2026 and reports annual recurring revenue in the tens of millions of dollars, positioning it as a mid-size, well-capitalized independent player rather than the largest name in its category. A major turning point in Gladly's product strategy came with its acquisition of Thankful, a generative AI and no-code automation company, which the two companies had already been partnering on since 2020 to power personalized service at scale for shared customers. That acquisition became the foundation for Gladly Sidekick, announced in July 2023, an AI and automation platform that sits alongside Gladly's original agent-facing product (now referred to as Gladly Hero) to handle common, repetitive customer inquiries such as order status questions and return requests without human involvement, freeing human agents to focus on conversations that genuinely require empathy, judgment, or complex problem-solving. Together, Hero and Sidekick represent Gladly's two-sided approach to AI in customer service: augmenting the human agent experience on one side, and deflecting or fully automating routine volume on the other. Gladly's customer base skews toward consumer-facing retail, e-commerce, and direct-to-consumer brands that see customer service as a driver of loyalty and lifetime value rather than a pure cost center; publicly referenced customers and partners include Crate & Barrel, JOANN, Bombas, Breeze Airways, and MaryRuth Organics. This focus differentiates Gladly from broader horizontal platforms like Zendesk, Salesforce Service Cloud, or Intercom, which serve a much wider range of industries including B2B software, and from newer AI-first customer support startups that lack Gladly's decade of experience with the unified-timeline data model. On pricing, Gladly does not publish a self-serve rate card and does not offer a free plan or public free trial for its core enterprise platform; prospective customers must go through sales. Third-party pricing research consistently places the entry-level Hero plan at around 180 dollars per agent per month, billed annually, with a minimum commitment of 10 agents, while a higher Superhero tier runs approximately 210 dollars per user per month with a 45-user minimum, reflecting Gladly's focus on mid-market and enterprise customers rather than small businesses. Voice and SMS usage, including call minutes, IVR usage, and international calling, are typically billed separately on top of the base per-agent price, and final contract pricing varies considerably based on channel mix and contract size. Separately, Gladly also offers a self-serve, usage-based small-business option distributed through the Shopify App Store, aimed at smaller e-commerce merchants; that plan includes a 30-day free trial followed by usage-based pricing of roughly 1.50 dollars per AI resolution, 0.25 dollars per AI assist, and 120 dollars per agent seat per month, all governed by a spend cap the merchant sets, which is a materially different and more accessible pricing structure than the core enterprise product. In the competitive landscape, Gladly is most often evaluated against Zendesk, Intercom, Kustomer, Salesforce Service Cloud, and Freshdesk, as well as against dedicated AI customer service automation vendors. Its key differentiators are the ticketless, timeline-based data model; the tight product integration between Hero (human-agent workspace) and Sidekick (AI automation), both born from the same underlying customer conversation data; and a go-to-market focus on brands that treat customer service as a revenue and loyalty lever rather than a support cost to be minimized. The trade-offs customers weigh against those strengths are Gladly's lack of a free tier, its relatively high per-agent price point compared to some horizontal help desk tools, and minimum seat commitments that put it out of reach for very small teams, all of which position Gladly primarily as a platform for growth-stage to enterprise consumer brands with dedicated, well-resourced customer service organizations.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'd4ff1377-e0f5-4af0-9e80-71487c351c04';

