-- в”Ђв”Ђ Glassbox в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Glassbox is an enterprise digital experience analytics platform offering session replay, customer journey analytics, and AI-powered fraud and struggle detection, built primarily for regulated industries like banking and insurance.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Contact for pricing$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$200-300 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Petah Tikva, Israel$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Glassbox Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Glassbox review 2026: enterprise session replay and customer analytics for regulated industries, pricing, features, pros, cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Glassbox is an Israeli digital experience analytics company founded in 2010 by Yoav Schreiber, Yaron Gueta, and Hanan Blumstein, headquartered in Petah Tikva, Israel, with additional offices historically maintained in London and New York. The company builds what it calls customer intelligence software: technology that automatically captures a complete, video-like replay of every user session on a website or mobile app, alongside the underlying technical events (network calls, errors, page loads) happening behind the scenes, so that product, customer experience, and support teams can see exactly what a real user encountered, without needing to guess from aggregate analytics dashboards or ask the user to reproduce a bug. Rather than pursuing a broad, horizontal customer-experience market, Glassbox positioned itself early around highly regulated industries where session-level visibility carries outsized value: financial services, insurance, government, telecom, airlines, and utilities. The company states that roughly 60 percent of the largest United States-based banks use its platform, and it counts global enterprises such as Air Canada and Marriott Hotels among its referenced customers, giving Glassbox a strong reputation specifically within banking, insurance, and other compliance-heavy verticals rather than as a general-purpose product analytics tool for startups. Glassbox's funding and corporate history is more eventful than most companies in its category. The company raised approximately 32.5 million dollars by October 2018, with backing from investors including Updata Partners, who took board seats as part of their investment. In April 2020, Glassbox raised a 40 million dollar Series C round explicitly earmarked to expand its digital-experience analytics capabilities. The company then went public in June 2021 on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, raising roughly 100 million dollars in its IPO at an implied valuation of about 500 million dollars, a notable milestone as one of the relatively few customer-analytics companies to pursue a public listing on that exchange rather than Nasdaq or NYSE. That public chapter did not last: in 2024, Glassbox was acquired and taken private again by the private equity firm Alicorn, returning the company to private ownership after roughly three years as a publicly traded entity. As of 2026, employee-count estimates for Glassbox range from around 200 to just under 300 people across various data sources, consistent with a mid-size enterprise software vendor. On the product side, Glassbox's centerpiece capability is Session Replay, which automatically records and reconstructs 100 percent of user interactions and technical events across both web and mobile app sessions, rather than relying on sampling. Layered on top of raw replay, the platform includes customer journey mapping to visualize how users move (or fail to move) through key funnels such as loan applications or account signups, heatmaps for visualizing where users click and where they hesitate, and struggle and friction detection to automatically flag sessions where users encountered errors, rage-clicked, or abandoned a process partway through. A more recent addition, the Glassbox Insights Assistant (GIA), applies AI to automatically summarize sessions and let analysts search across large volumes of recorded sessions using natural language rather than manually reviewing individual replays, addressing one of the classic scaling problems of session-replay tools: the sheer volume of recorded video becomes unusable without AI-assisted summarization and search. Given its regulated-industry focus, Glassbox also emphasizes fraud detection and anomaly identification, using machine learning to flag abnormal or irregular session activity in real time and giving fraud and security teams precise, replayable evidence of what happened during a suspicious session, a capability with particular resonance in banking and insurance where session-level forensic evidence can matter for both security investigations and regulatory compliance. Glassbox does not publish a self-serve pricing page or offer a free tier; all pricing is custom and quote-based, reflecting its enterprise, contract-driven sales motion. Third-party pricing benchmarks and industry estimates for comparable regulated-industry analytics platforms suggest costs in the range of roughly 3,000 to 12,000 dollars per month depending on traffic volume, feature set, and deployment requirements, though Glassbox itself does not confirm exact figures publicly, and actual enterprise contracts, especially for large banks, are likely to be negotiated well above self-service SaaS pricing norms. In the competitive landscape, Glassbox is most frequently compared to Contentsquare, FullStory, Quantum Metric, Decibel, and Medallia, all of which offer some combination of session replay, digital experience analytics, and customer journey insight. Glassbox differentiates itself from these more horizontally focused competitors through its dedicated emphasis on regulated, compliance-sensitive industries, deep session-level fraud and security detection capabilities, and a customer base and go-to-market motion built specifically around banks, insurers, telecoms, and government agencies rather than e-commerce or general SaaS product teams, which tend to be the primary audience for competitors like FullStory or Contentsquare. This regulated-industry specialization is both Glassbox's core differentiator and the primary lens through which its roadmap, pricing, and customer references should be understood.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '32c09a08-ca8d-4425-b7ea-3b78968f97a4';

